#gitignore .gitignore
# Plan (pseudocode) - detailed steps describing what this .gitignore will contain:
# 1. Provide high-level comments describing intent: exclude IDE-specific, OS, build, package, and user-secret files.
# 2. Add Visual Studio / .NET specific patterns:
#    - exclude build outputs: bin/, obj/, [**/]bin/, [**/]obj/
#    - exclude Visual Studio workspace and user files: *.suo, *.user, *.userosscache, *.sln.docstates
#    - exclude .vs/ hidden folder used by VS for workspace data
# 3. Add NuGet and package manager artifacts:
#    - exclude packages/ (legacy), obj project assets, *.nupkg, project.lock.json, package.lock.json
#    - exclude global NuGet caches and .nuget/ if present
# 4. Add IDE/editor folders: .vscode/, .idea/, .Rider/, _ReSharper*/
# 5. Add test, coverage, and profiler outputs: TestResults/, coverage.*, *.trx, *.coverage, nunit-*.xml
# 6. Add build and publish outputs: PublishArtifacts/, /publish/, *.deploypkg, *.zip from publish
# 7. Add dotnet and tooling caches: .dotnet/, .dotnet_tool_restore.json, .dotnet/buildlogs/
# 8. Add system OS files: .DS_Store, Thumbs.db, desktop.ini, ehthumbs.db
# 9. Add dependency managers and language-specific: node_modules/, npm-debug.log, yarn-error.log, .pnp.*, dist/, lib/, .cache/
# 10. Add sensitive files and local config: appsettings.Development.json, user secrets store, *.key, *.pfx
# 11. Add CI/CD, container and logs: docker-compose.override.yml (local), *.log, logs/, docker image files
# 12. Add common tooling caches: .cache/, .terraform/, .pytest_cache/, .mypy_cache/
# 13. Provide clear section headers and examples; keep patterns recursive where appropriate.
#
# Implementation: translate the above rules into common, well-tested gitignore patterns for Visual Studio/.NET projects
#
# Note: If your project contains additional folders (e.g. `src/`, `backend/`, `frontend/`) consider adding their build artifacts explicitly.

